Brainstorming more apparatuses and gadgets for my bodybuilder lifestyle product line. Coffee French press, but extra-strength, with good leverage, and you get to really pulverize the ground coffee in there. 60 lbs. Tungsten bowling ball. Progressive overload heavy steering wheel.

Stuff like "frying pan, but heavier" is too simplistic. Something like an assisted pull-up machine toilet seat makes more sense. Or a leg press/hack squat toilet seat. Skateboard squats shower. Heavy mechanical keyboard keys. Already exists. 280g APC Tai-Hao Clicky Blue switches.

Apparently "Cherry MX Green Key Switches" require 80g of force to press down to the trigger. "Tactile grays" are 110 grams. MX Super Blacks 150 grams. There are apparently some 1700g custom ones on Thockpop. Imagine having to press 2 kilograms down with one finger each keystroke.

I remember watching a documentary about an English beef broth street salesman. Like he had a small booth outside, similar to a lemonade stand, and a big cauldron of beef broth brewing all day. You pay him 0.50 pounds and he pours you a cup of hot broth. Beautiful business idea.

Pretty sure it was a local family tradition thing, where his dad was a broth booth salesman too. But imagine being able to just get a cup of steaming beef broth on a winter day, when you're cold walking outside, must warm you up so nicely. Flushes the face like hot coffee or tea.

From my roadtrip a few weeks ago. An official document of the local Orthodox diocese, nailed to a post next to the small chapel, announcing an increase in the sales price of church candles, to accord them to the bulk paraffin wax market price. The brutal economy of New Jerusalem!

It just struck me as something profoundly spiritual. The Church of Christ having to adapt to everyday market conditions, tinker with the prices of the smallest items, count cents, candles, and coins, like a beggar in poverty. The most mundane reveals a great attitude of eternity!
